His body is two-dimensional and squeaky-colored.
Gravity no longer has any power over him, he floats on the ceiling.
He senses a kick.
Behind him, winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted faces, teeth-snagging.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he senses the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar out of walls and radio.
He can no longer bear them, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. tears two cables out of the stereo, knots them into a sling and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs a loudspeaker and puts the sling around his neck.
Jump.
The noose is loosening.
This is supposed to be a lesson to you, screaming the voices in drum-shattering choir, "go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today is Henning T. 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychosis, the last one is 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, and he is also manic-depressive, he takes medication, for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The illusions are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, in psychiatric clinics she is treated as the second most common condition after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outside world, they fall into an overexcited state, which can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship or persecution.
Particularly common is voice hearing - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not rare.
The affected person can no longer separate the important from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time, he is in a passive role, he is, much like in a dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A reality comparison is usually not possible for them, the illusions are cruel reality, awakening excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality perceived in psychosis is fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of experience takes place in the real frame.
Why exactly our brain beats capriciousness, researchers still find puzzles.
States of emergency can lead to a temporary loss of the reality of every human being, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the sole determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal ripening of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, for example, Fuchs explains.
But it remains a mystery how the disturbance of the neural system comes about, which also does not manifest itself at first for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains are hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive medications to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether mirages are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and deceit for ten years, and last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of amazingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, this often includes diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's and traumatic brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memory content that is usually withheld.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or inhibited; when our brains run hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also stimulus withdrawal, stress, heartbreak or other mental states of emergency.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents said they had experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and voices.
During the break, it can happen that a slug boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the appearances are mostly scary
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the subject matter of instruction, because the teacher is just introducing a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while he explains mathematical equations for everyone else to hear and visible on the board.
At night, the appearances are mostly scary.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees arise the faces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she yells at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell them about it, they would think they're crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed the Abitur last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she made contact with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows full well that she is not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art out of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimulus withdrawal, they are most likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is then underwhelmed and provides for its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often she played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she calls dad since she can remember is not her biological father.
Since the same brain areas are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations that also process real impressions and sounds, those affected, such as Sarah K., find it difficult to distinguish illusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is reflected there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
Even nightly dream images considers Kasten as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their deceits as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to value the hallucinations as a special ability.
The boundary between dream and hallucination
In our too much mind-centered world, imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also harbors positive, creative things - madness is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of trauma-like changed waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by self- and world loss, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a change of world takes place, but the real situation is presented in the imagination.
An intense form of meaning-making and meaning in an unbearable situation that allows us humans to develop their own ability not to perish in a nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Change" as a rescue operation of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation with subsequent heart transplant, while his body in the intensive care unit is condemned to motionlessness.
Claussen immerses himself in a self-created world, visiting strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make intoxicants from blood.
If a Greek is carried away by a Greek on a motorcycle in his home country, surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He goes completely into the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream for Claussen.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travel are still clear to me after years and in incidental details.
More clearly and more intensely even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations and drug frenzy show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also in waking.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist caste concludes, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
