75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination in work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain" conducted by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women's Affairs.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labor market restricted due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and, if so, what kind of profession they practice.
Those of them who do not do any other activity outside the house, work only half-day or have no fixed employment contract, are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, the women with a permanent job, especially in the public sphere, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
“The women in the age group between 35 and 49 years with a permanent job do not have their first child on average 3.7 years after contracting, a number that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent employment, who have taken longer to achieve this and who have come to terms with her and the first child has only realized much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major impact on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of willingness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be noted among women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they only have the primary school degree or a higher education, became a mother for the first time on average with 25.1 or 32.1 respectively.
Furthermore, depending on their level of education, there is another difference between women.
While the women with a main degree already get married before their first permanent employment and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree make it exactly the other way around and first look for a permanent job and get married afterwards and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
