CNMV approves the public exclusion tender submitted by the investment company Mer by Paternina
The National Exchange Commission (CNMV) approved the public exclusion tender for Federico Paternina submitted by the investment company Mer last 9. October.
The supervisory authority stated that it approved this invitation to tender after it had been demonstrated that the conditions comply with the legally binding laws and thus the content of the explanatory supplement submitted, following the amendments of the last 2. December, can be considered "sufficient."
CNMV has also announced that this offer is aimed at the acquisition of 550,000 shares of Federico Paternina at a price of €7.65 per share, which in turn is 8.95% of the share capital, which is composed of €6,142,786 in shares admitted on the Madrid and Bilbao stock exchanges.
In addition, it was also announced that 5,592,778 million shares have been permanently invested, which cannot be transferred in any way until the conclusion of the tender and the price of which was fixed by Federico Paternina in accordance with the legally binding laws.
New programs for the assessment of vehicles
These days of severe weather and accidents not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed to the workshops, where an appraiser must assess the damage incurred and the cost of repairing it.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including the parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest IT tools, it is a matter of minutes
This is why almost 100% of the reviewers use this type of systems.
Service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from the manufacturers in order to process it afterwards and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all expert reports are prepared with their products.
The other two companies competing with the tool market for review and preparation of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales manager of Audatex, works with 63 manufacturers and importers, with each of them providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is getting larger, to the point that even more versions, variants and engines have been launched in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car is launched, work begins for the companies.
It is a tedious task, because every single one of the thousands of vehicle parts must be catagolized and entered its price.
In addition, a "smart" graphic image is created from each model, on which you can "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If this is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. At present, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, they have information about the Porsche models, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the vehicle fleet travelling on the road, it is over 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out the documentation work and the production of databases, Audatex has eight centers distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics professionals) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests €90 million annually in the preparation of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers get the updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information enables companies to use it in various ways and thereby offer different products.
The most common use is the use for the repairs and repairs, however, depending on the country, there are also tools for the management of scrap parts or for calculating the file or residual value of a car.
The only company that informs about a guide who informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products that Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the kind of support it gives to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products being AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for the reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles, as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the paint prices.
This tool is paid for depending on the purpose, i.e. for each report.
It will be the most expensive for customers who rarely use it, a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, every insurance company that prepares thousands of expert reports negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran off the assembly line, solely on the basis of the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is an open service on the Internet for the specialist market, with which you can offer vehicles that have been declared a total loss.
Your statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses, or for obtaining information about the deviations by brand and model.
One can use it to investigate, for example, how many models of a particular car brand had to go to the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to developing this type of computer tools.
It distributes, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and supplies digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer in the same way.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, which in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns and/or Maintenance of vehicles was established.
The GT leader for expert opinions is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 reviewers and 53 insurance companies.
Their business volume has increased at 20% annually in the last three years and in 2008 sales amounted to EUR 10.8 million.
At the beginning of last year, they began to go to the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its business is done in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
Total revenue in the world of the Solera group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) is $557 million, up 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange and today its shares are traded at a value of $2.4 billion.
They have been on the New York Stock Exchange since 2007 and part of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
